AIC Model Selection

Sarah Zirkle

October 1, 2021

Tri-colored bat habitat use

Tri-colored bat

The first data set is once again my own. I am looking at habitat selection at the tree level. This includes includes one response variables: use. My data is in the binomial data as use is 0/1.

The data includes six predictor variables: dbh (diameter breast height), height (roost tree (m)), slope, decay stage (1-9), and canopy (% cover).

All of these variables have been cited as important parts of tree selection for various bat species in the Southeastern U.S.

Lets check for co-linearity among the predictor variables.

pairs(bats[,2:6], lower.panel = NULL)

Seems ok but...... dbh and height look awfully correlated so lets check.

cor(bats$height, bats$dbh)
## [1] 0.6600357

They have a pretty high correlation. Therefore, lets not include both in the same model. / / Lets look at the deviance.

model_bat1 <- glm(use ~ dbh + decay + canopy + height + slope, family = binomial(link="logit"), data=bats)
anova (model_bat1) 
## Analysis of Deviance Table

Our VIF looks fine for this dataset.

We can now fit some candidate models to explain variation in use.

mod1<-glm(use~height, family = binomial(link="logit"), data = bats)
mod2<-glm(use~height+slope, family = binomial(link="logit"), data = bats)
mod3<-glm(use~height+decay, family = binomial(link="logit"), data = bats)
mod4<-glm(use~height+canopy, family = binomial(link="logit"), data = bats)

We will now use model select to conduct model selection.

out.put<-model.sel(mod1,mod2,mod3,mod4)
out.put
## Model selection table

These are the models ranked. Looks like mod1, containing an intercept (Int) and height (roost tree height (m)) is best with a weight of 0.462. It is 0.462/0.204 = 2.26 times more likely to be the best explanation (hypothesis) for variation in tree use.

Red panda habitat use

Red panda

For my second example researchers looked at the Red Panda, an endangered habitat specialist, that inhabits a narrow distribution range in bamboo forests along mountain slopes in the Himalaya and Hengduan Mountains.

Their habitat use is different in places with different longitudinal environmental gradients, climatic regimes, and microclimate. In their paper they compared different regions but I chose just to look at their data from Western Nepal.

This subset of data includes the response variable of richness. Five predictor variables are: TreeHigh (tree height), DBH (diameter breast height), Canopy (canopy coverage), BamboAbun (bamboo abundance), and TreeSpeciesRichness (tree species richness).

This study aimed to determine the habitat variables affecting red panda distribution across different longitudinal gradients through a multivariate analysis.

Hopes for the outcome of this study is to highlight the need of importance of bamboo conservation and site pecific conservation planning to ensure long term red panda conservation.

panda <- read.csv("RedPandaSurveyData.csv")
View(panda)
ggpairs(panda, columns = 2:6) + theme_bw()

model_panda1 <- lm(richness ~ TreeHigh + DBH + Canopy + BamboAbun + TreeSpeciesRichness, data=panda)
anova (model_panda1) 
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: richness

## TreeSpeciesRichness   1     9.1   9.134  0.1078 0.7431

We can check for multicollinearity.

performance::check_collinearity(model_panda1)
## # Check for Multicollinearity
## 
## Low Correlation
## 
##            Parameter  VIF Increased SE
##             TreeHigh 1.12         1.06
##                  DBH 1.43         1.20
##               Canopy 1.48         1.22
##            BamboAbun 1.06         1.03
##  TreeSpeciesRichness 1.17         1.08

Our VIF is less than 5 indicating a low correlation of that predictor with other predictors.

Now, lets set up our models.

m1<-lm(richness ~ Canopy + DBH +BamboAbun + TreeSpeciesRichness, data = panda)
m2<-lm(richness~Canopy + TreeHigh +DBH + BamboAbun + TreeSpeciesRichness, data = panda)
m3<-lm(richness~DBH + BamboAbun + TreeSpeciesRichness, data = panda)
m4<-lm(richness~TreeHigh + TreeSpeciesRichness + Canopy, data = panda)
out.put1<-model.sel(m1,m2,m3,m4)
out.put1
